A modern take on Cantonese cuisine. The most unique dish is squid ink fried rice. Other good dishes include King Do spare ribs, beef stir fry flat noodles, and wonton soup. Prices are slightly higher than some old Chinatown establishments, but you're paying more for the modern decor than the taste.
Best breakfast hash I've ever had.  And they played the dukes of Hazzard theme song during my meal, whats better than that?

So far I like the look of it but I can't wait to actually eat there

Apart from being absolutely charming and sparkling clean, this focused menu is fantastic.  I had the Hog Head Cheese Grit Bowl.  If you do something simple like this, every component has to be perfect.  And.  It.  Was.  Best grits I've had outside of my grandma's kitchen with actual poached eggs and a big fluffy biscuit.  The hogshead cheese was a surprising delicacy and ffffffffresh!  Guy taking orders was delightful and the chef asked if wanted it extra spicy.  Took it home and hunkered down on a rainy Sunday afternoon.  Perfection.

Good food, with a good selection. They have a three course meal that comes with half an appetizer, entree and dessert that was decently priced. They DON'T serve alcohol, however you can bring your own and they charge $10 per bottle of wine or six pack of beer.
Extremely good pancakes, good service and overall good restaurant.

Great little place. It's BYOB, with a reasonable corkage fee so be warned, but the food more than makes up for it.  I had the BBQ shrimp, chicken fried steak and mac n cheese. I have to mention first the chicken fried steak because it was one of the best I've ever had; the batter was awesome. I got the gravy on the side and basically didn't touch it the chicken was so moist and delicious. The mac n cheese were very tasty too, and the BBQ shrimp were great. They are greasy (as BBQ shrimp in New Orleans should be) and you have to peel them, but very tasty.  The bathroom was spotless as well, which is a definite +++++  Great experience. Can't wait to go back.
Great comfort food.
Note it's a "BYOB" kind of thing. Food was good; service was off.

Skip this place. There are so many wonderful options in the area and Eat New Orleans is the worst. The food was bland and poached eggs were cold. The service is exceptionally slow. Bad coffee was also cold. Bland chicken and bland shrimp and grits.
Amazing food! Great flavor. Really great service!
Very good food
Unbelievable food (some of the best in NOLA). Friendly staff!!!

Great little spot for some good soul food and a cozy atmosphere.

Fast and friendly service, delicious butterbeans, great gumbo too. Some items, like the white rice and baked macaroni and cheese, were a little dry. Good quick option if you are in the Quarter and don't want a fancy 2 hour candlelit dinner.
Love, love, love this place. Great environment, great staff and the food was incredible. Eat will be the one place that will be mandatory every time we visit.

The Morrison has a great atmosphere.  We saw a sign for burgers, beer, and they have a parking lot. This place is overall an enjoyable restaurant with atmosphere and good food. French fries that taste like bbq potatoes chips. The burgers are a half pound, cooked just as you ask them to be and served on a brioche bun. Best bread pudding you will find. Nick. Great guy, very helpful.  I highly recommend stopping by this place! If you're in the area, go to the Morrison.

I loved how they are successful in the happy hour, something simple, good taste, good quality & good customer service and on top on that they take care of your dogs by feeding them...what else do you want to get ?...the price it's very fair so you won't get disappointed
I Love this place right here.

During the winter time, I crave a lot of red curry. So I've been trying out different places and Kang Thai is the top winner! It's tucked away in a food court next to a car wash but I just got my food to go. I can't wait to try more from them.

I love this place. I've gone here several times and each time is great. The place has a very "homey" feel. You feel very welcomed when you first walk and are greeted. The food is delicious and taste very authentic. They have an entertainer that plays the accordion and is hysterical with his made up songs based on the people at the table. I love coming to this place!
Tasty food, friendly staff. Highly recommended if you are around the French quarter and want to eat some fresh and well cooked food.

From the beginning to the end and everything in between. All the staff front and back. The cohesiveness of pairing of all flavors the tenderness of the lamb the freshness of pasta the softness and aromatic of the bread. The combination of different spices and the sweetness of the persimmon. And the teamwork the flow of the staff attention to details made this dining experience exceptional.
Great and tasty experience with local cuisine highlights and great concept with the restaurant.
Small, cute place. They have great brunch with amazing food.
That the food is great

One of my favorite eateries in the Big Easy! I come here every time I visit my family in New Orleans. Last time, I had eggs dauphine on top of boudin and collard greens. To die for! Love the service as well, and it is very gay friendly! Please, indulge yourself in the simplicity of fine Louisiana cuisine and chow down at Eat New Orleans.

A quaint little restaurant... I thought I would order the ribs but it was way overdone and had to get another dish. The waitress was really kind about switching but anyway spent $30 on two halves of a stuffed pepper and french fries. Used to be a Zagat rated restaurant. A little disappointed.

My quiche was mediocre but my husband’s meal was very good. He ordered the Trio. There were no high chairs for our baby but they have booster seats for older children. This place has won the best meal on my weekend trip to New Orleans. To be honest, I didn't expect much. It was located on the edge of the French Quarters and didn't have a crowd like the popular Acme Oyster House. I loved the menu options, they offer a pixie fix (3-course meal), normal entree, dinner options, etc. The service was great and the atmosphere was classy, clean and casual.

This place is a Gem right on Dumaine.  Boyfriend and I came here the first night we were on vacation after just taking a chance on a Google Search, his first time in New Orleans, my second.  We were not disappointed!  The food was amazing!  I had a seafood pasta which was perfectly prepared, and our waiter was was great and interactive despite having a full restaurant.  It upsets me to see so many people talking about rude staff.  10/10 would go back!

Mind you, the place was completely empty when we walked in. Our server had terrible timing on everything from taking our orders, to sounding confident in communicating to us, to bringing our food to the table, to getting our orders correct, to making it right when he had to be informed that he had gotten our orders wrong. The place is very nice. But, everything else was severely lacking.

Oh man, I can still taste it.  Do yourself a favor and get over to this place as soon as possible.  The crawfish bisque is pretty damn good to just for your information.   Let me know what you think!

I visit Eat every visit to New Orleans despite it not having a liquor license...the food is too good to miss out on, and there is no shortage of bars within easy walking distance. The menu is relatively small, but everything is cooked to perfection, and I get to try out some of those delicate`cies that are so rare back home in the UK, such as blackened catfish on the latest trip.

Great place! Not a huge menu, but what they serve is all good. Local farm to table type place. No alcohol, but there is a store a block away and BYOB is perfectly fine. Portions are generous. We had the red fish and smoked BBQ ribs, finished with a peach/blueberry cobler. This is one place we always try to revisit when we come to New Orleans.

We ate supper here on a Friday night and were able to easily secure a table for three. My party had the burgers and vegan burger, the spicy deviled egg appetizer, and shared a piece of probably the best chocolate cake ever, plus it was warm and gooey. Efficient well-paced service and nice portions. Great, attentive service. Nice, comfortable small restaurant. My scallop special with poached eggs and cornbread was outstanding. Loved the lime curd with biscuits, too. Great meal with friends!

Absolutely excellent! We were wandering in the area and stumbled upon this place. Sooooo good, nice staff. I had crab cakes Benedict and my husband had the fried green tomato breakfast. Definitely recommend this place!

I absolutely love this place and the food here is delicious see of the best I have in NOLA. The restaurant is very quaint and somewhat deep in the quarter. The food is real down south comfort food. So you may wonder why only four stars. It's because they don't serve liquor. They're BYOB. If you have no plans to have a drink with your meal then it's not a problem but if you do then it's a bummer. Because you want to stay here and have some drinks and good food with company and enjoy the ambiance. Nevertheless you should eat here.

Went with my Bachlorette party group, we had called 3 other places looking to for a place for dinner and everyone had 2+ hr waits. We looked of places with high star counts and this place popped up on our radar. The food was delicious. EVERYTHING I had was amazing and i ordered the gumbo, catfish, and mashed potatoes. Some of the ladies ordered different meals so we could try each others out. I recommend trying the banana cream pie. It was my favorite. I also enjoyed the hush puppies (boulettes) and fried green tomatoes. They were really kind and accommodating.

A couple before us knocked. A guy came and unlocked the door, slung it open with an attitude and said I was going to open it. We went in but quickly decided to leave because of how rudely we were treated. Confronted the man and he said we were impatient. He was not apologetic at all for making us wait and opening late. The owner should be made aware that they have lost us my group plus the other couple that knocked on the door.

For perfectly prepared southern food with noticeably high-quality ingredients, there’s hardly a restaurant in town that beats this place. Located on a quiet corner, this place can get crowded quickly, but it’s worth the wait. I especially love brunch and fried green tomatoes!
Great place for brunch in the weekend.

Definitely go on a weekend for breakfast/brunch.  It is absolutely delicious.  I had biscuits with gravy that were life changing.   Breakfast is not served on weekdays though.

I am not a salad person but while visiting NOLA all I ate was pastries, baguettes and pizza I thought it was time to have a healthy meal. I was very hesitant to order salad as I usually regret my decision immediately and don’t finish my plate. I have to say I was super impressed at the quality of the food. I highly recommend their salad with fresh avocados, bacon, egg, cheese and chicken. Talk about delicious & fulfilling!

More typically, they've been indifferent to rude. Bottom line: this is a great place if you don't care about those pesky little things like more than 6 oz of water at your meal (cuz you ain't gettin no refill), people making eye contact, smiling, or generally giving you the impression they want you there. Or for that matter, getting change. Last time I was there, my bill was $13 something. I gave the waiter a $20. Ten minutes later, I asked where my change was. Eye roll. "Oh, you wanted change?"

Food was great, dessert was fantastic, service was wonderful!! There were three of us and we all ordered different dishes with different meats and all three dishes were delicious. Make sure you save room for dessert because it is 100% worth it!

Been going here for years, whenever I visit New Orleans.  Always amazing.  Small place just outside of the worst of the tourist hustle.    You may have to wait for a table, but well worth it. One of my favs in a city of great restaurants! Great for couples, friends or families.  Highly recommended.

Charming restaurant, excellent service by Starr.  The food is for the most part reasonably priced, sandwiches and a side around $14, dinner specials $27 including an average Caesar salad (no parmesan croute).  The avocado gazpacho was a creamy dream.  Desserts are simple and substantial.  Corkage fee is reasonable.  Only 1 bathroom, looked like the ceiling was leaking in the hallway leading to it.  Mopping more often instead of just a wet floor sign is one of the reasons only 4 not 5 stars given.  The Mac and cheese side looked lacklustre.  Good choice for the shrimp and bean soup, salads are lovely and substantial, menu offers options for vegetarians and those that are gluten free.

Walked in alone. Both servers in the area I sat in made eye contact. One put up one finger for “single diner” and I nodded and he pointed to a table. I sat for 5 minutes with no contact. Then two women walked in and were seated and had their drink order taken and their drinks delivered and their food order taken, all the while I was desperately making eye contact with both servers while they were taking orders and bringing food to other people in the section but never even brought me a menu. I was with a group visiting New Orleans and wanted to eat somewhere close on our lunch break.  Somehow this restaurant had strong reviews and a high rating.  The server was attentive, at first, but when a slight modification to an item was given it went bad.   We ordered four veggie burgers and three were delivered, with the sides wrong. Food Hounds... when in Rome - eat like the Romans do; but when you're in New Orleans, Louisiana... EAT Creole & Cajun!!!  This little restaurant on Dumaine Street in the French Quarter called 'Eat NOLA' hit the spot with some incredible Southern Cajun soul food.  A very quaint location with roughly twenty tables, the overall vibe of the restaurant was laid back and enjoyable.  For starters, we had the Crawfish Boullettes - little crawfish hushpuppies of love, fried lightly and filled with a blend of taste bud pleasing goodness.  The true bonus came while each bite was accompanied by an unreal Remoulade Sauce!  Next was the Chicken and Andouille Gumbo; better known as Gumbo Yaya (because there is no oakra).  This gumbo was utterly outstanding!  Healthy helpings of moist chicken and sausage that literally fell apart in my mouth, fantastic flavor with a slight creep of spicy love for good measure (this IS NOLA after all).  The side of rice was soft, moist and perfect for sopping up all the extra juices!  The WIN for me right off the bat was the Fried Catfish - crisp, moist, plump and bursting with natural flavors that were not overly fishy.  This specific dish was extremely light and airy; especially for a fried treat.  I must admit that I devoured the delectable delights of the sea and enjoyed their homemade tartar sauce.   The Pork Tenderloin was not only doused with caramelized onions; but was moist, not overly seasoned and very pleasant - the onions created a sweet and savory addition to each and every bite for a very well-rounded dish!  A great side to the pork was their homemade Mac & Cheese; an interesting take on an old classic - thin macaroni with flavoring that had my taste buds doing the Tango!  The Flatiron Steak was done to perfection while retaining its yummy juices - lightly seasoned and slightly soaked with an herb-ish butter; the heaping side of Garlic Smashed Potatoes was lightly salted, lumpy and offered a hint of garlic!  As for the BBQ Shrimp, be prepared for a little bit of a mess - these hefty shrimp are soaked in the 'bomb' sauce (WIN) which is a butter meets paprika blend with a touch of hot sauce; these peel your own shrimp are delectable and delightful!  Make sure to order the Fried Green Tomatoes as they were large, fresh and juicy tomatoes that were served warm, crispy and bursting with flavor in a doughy shell.  Now you know you are in Louisiana when it's time for dessert and out comes slices of cake that are almost as big as the pie-hole your about to shove them into!  All their desserts are homemade and I have to admit guiltily... utterly delicious!  The German Double Chocolate Cake was astounding!  Moist and decadent with sweet, rich flavor that left a smile on my face; especially with the addition of a coconut outer rim that blew me away!  Next up was the Three Nut Pecan Pie - ZOMG... sweet and chewy caramel love, drizzled over a pie erected by none other than almonds, walnuts and pecans - what a wonderful and completely enjoyable meal.  If you are looking to have a few drinks with your meal, make sure to hit up a liquor store prior to visiting - Eat has no liquor license; however they do happen to be BYOB (although uncorking fees are applicable).  We'd certainly recommend people to check out everything that Eat NOLA has to offer... certainly a great place to break bread with family or friends!

Highly recommended by friend and it was worthy praise. Our waiter Brian was very helpful and attentive. The Cochon on greens was delicious. Loved the fried green tomatoes...crispy and with phenomenal house remoulade AND topped with shrimp damn fine. We had 3 desserts...but hey it is Nawlins..."carmel fruited cake" was oohhygooey deliciousness. Good bread pudding and the "soaked" raisins far exceeded their grape's lives expectations. Winner was the hazelnut torte pie...wow so chocolatey and smooth. Thanks!
